## Location
firmware/bridge-zephyr/subsys/lichen/lichen_util.h:51-52

## Issue
The word-aligned optimization in `secure_zero()` has a redundant alignment check inside the bulk-write loop:

```c
while (len >= 32) {
    /* Align to word boundary first */
    while (len > 0 && ((uintptr_t)p & (sizeof(unsigned long) - 1)) != 0) {
        *p++ = 0;
        len--;
    }
    /* Word-sized writes for the bulk (only if properly aligned) */
    while (len >= sizeof(unsigned long) &&
           ((uintptr_t)p & (sizeof(unsigned long) - 1)) == 0) {  // <-- redundant
        *(volatile unsigned long *)p = 0;
        ...
```

After the first while loop completes, `p` is guaranteed to be word-aligned (or `len` is 0). The alignment check in line 51-52 is always true (or the loop is never entered due to `len` check), wasting cycles on every iteration of the inner loop.

## What goes wrong
- Minor CPU waste on every call with len >= 32 (not a security bug, but suboptimal)
- Pattern may be copied by contributors to other security-critical paths where performance matters more
- Creates confusion about whether the alignment guarantee from the first loop is trusted

## Fix
Remove the redundant alignment check from the bulk-write while condition:
```c
while (len >= sizeof(unsigned long)) {
    *(volatile unsigned long *)p = 0;
    ...
```
